<TITLE> European shares rise early, driven by miners, M&A </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, April 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares rose in early trade on Monday, building on the previous session's gains, as British Energy jumped on bid talk and miners advanced on higher metal prices and bullish brokerage comment. At 0717 GMT, the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares was up 0.6 percent at 1,325.91 points. Anglo American, BHP Billiton, Vedanta, Kazakhmys, Antofagasta and Rio Tinto all notched up gains of 2 to 4 percent, with the sector driven by a positive note from Goldman Sachs. Embattled Swiss bank UBS gained 4.3 percent after a Merrill Lynch upgrade, while British Energy rose 3.5 percent on a newspaper report that Centrica had launched talks with France's EDF over a joint bid for it. Nestle rose 3.3 percent after striking a deal to sell a stake in eyecare group Alcon to Swiss peer Novartis, while Novartis rose 1 percent. L'Oreal topped European gainers with a 4.4 percent rise on speculation that Nestle would raise its stake in the group, traders said
